label chapter20:

    # [Scene: Promenade | Night]

    scene bg ch12_735866_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Percussive, urgent drums under a high, whistling string ostinato]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Thin alarm pings from the Beacon, then wind tearing at tarps; gulls cry, distorted]
    "You came back here because the map in your head would not leave you alone. Tonight the map is alive — a living atlas of valves and seams, of neighbor's porches and which roofs you think"
    "can survive a night like this. The Beacon's feed has been howling for hours. You press the compass into the hollow of your palm until the brass bites."
    "The air tastes of iron and rain and something older — seaweed and the ghost of smoked fish. Each inhale is a promise and a threat at once: act, or watch the town be rewritten by the tide."

    scene bg ch12_735866_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Wood creaks; ropes strain; someone shouts a name that answers back across the boards]
    show noah_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_reyes "Asha—here. Tether the line to the piling, not the railing. Railing comes loose."
    "Noah's voice cuts through the noise, steady but thin. He's leaned into a task like he's always leaned into people — hands first, words after. He catches your eye when you hesitate and there is no"
    "time for the soft, private thing that sometimes lives between you; there is only the practical covenant of staying alive."
    "You move like a machine someone learned to wind up: one motion after another. Sandbags into place. Reed mats hauled, edges trimmed with wet hands. You smell wet rope and the diesel tang of Lila's high-capacity pumps somewhere beyond the boardwalk, their engines a low, clinical bass under the storm."
    show marta_chen at right:
        zoom 0.7

    marta_chen "Waist-deep on the east side! If the current takes the mat, haul hard on three—one, two—"
    "Marta is a human roar. She doesn't ask for fidelity to plans; she demands the next right motion. Volunteers obey. You obey. Eli hauls a plank, muscles burning, face stung by rain. His mouth sets into"
    "a line that says too much history for tonight. He doesn't look at the Beacon; he looks at the boards as if at old bones."
    hide noah_reyes
    hide marta_chen

    scene bg ch12_735866_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Metallic clank of engineered beams; the Beacon blares another alert]
    show lila_park at left:
        zoom 0.7

    lila_park "We can shore the breach here. If we run the anchors across the gap and drop the deployables, we can hold the west channel."
    "You look at her, at the slope of her jaw, at the water she wants to tell where to stop. The corporate crew moves like a different species: efficient, luminous vests, hands that belong to systems not stories. Lila's eyes flick to the volunteers, to Noah, to you."

    lila_park "We need clear lines. We can't have ad-hoc placements. It compromises structural integrity."
    "You feel a hot rod of anger spool under your ribs — not at her solution, at the idea of being overwritten. But you also feel exhaustion and the truth that a pump is a pump"
    "when the cellar fills and promises do not save people from drowning. The choice is a current pulling at both of you."
    "Noah interposes with both hands raised, palms out, the universal gesture of buying breathing room."
    show noah_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_reyes "We will work with you, Lila — but community oversight. No sealed datasets, no unilateral decisions. We stand shoulder-to-shoulder."
    "Lila hesitates. Her mouth tightens into a small line and you cannot tell if it is concession or calculation."

    lila_park "Fine. Field logs open. Live stream."
    "She gives nothing more than the phrase; you cannot read whether the concession is for optics or principle. When she looks at you, her expression is complex — a hard slate with a crack of something like respect, or perhaps impatience. The ambiguity sits between you like brackish water."

    menu:
        "Grab the nearest pump control and help Lila's crew":
            "You wedge your fingers under the cold panel, fingers numb; the pump answers with a shudder and a spray of seawater that soaks your jacket. Lila's technician nods once, almost like a greeting."
        "Run back to the volunteers and keep tending the reeds and planks":
            "You turn and sprint, mud slinging your boots. Marta catches your sleeve and hands you a soaked bundle of twine; it smells of moss and old labor and anchors you in a different kind of work."

    # --- merge ---
    "The scene continues at the breach."
    # [Scene: Boardwalk | Night — closer to the breach]
    hide lila_park
    hide noah_reyes

    scene bg ch12_735866_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Drums accelerate; high strings screech at the edges]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A wall of water bangs against a hastily assembled barrier; timbers snap like bones]
    "The first time the barrier takes a blow and holds, you let out a sound that is half relief and half warning. The second time it doesn't hold is an animal noise: lungs, a hand finding"
    "the world in panic. For a time you move like two people: the person who plans, and the animal who reacts. They are not the same, but they keep the town alive between them."
    show eli_duarte at left:
        zoom 0.7

    eli_duarte "Get the bulkhead! Pull the rope, Asha!"
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A hydraulic groan; the Beacon's alarm shifts into a higher register—urgent, insistent]
    hide eli_duarte

    scene bg ch12_735866_5 at full_bg
    "Noah is there beside you, voice a thread you can trace with your fingers."
    show noah_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_reyes "Fall back to the east line—now! The current's pulled under the foundation!"
    "You don't think. You move. Tethers cinch around waists. Volunteers hook into safety lines like a chorus, one after another, voices turning into a rhythm."
    show marta_chen at right:
        zoom 0.7

    marta_chen "Count heads! Count heads! If you slip, grab the buoy—don't reach for the ladder!"
    "People fall into choreography: someone repeats a name, someone repeats a number; the litany keeps panic from sprouting. In the chaos you find yourself pushing a child out of the flow with both arms, your jacket"
    "drenched, the child coughing salt and crying your name though you have never taught them to call you anything but 'Asha.'"
    "The breach widens. A storage container — corrugated, stamped with investor logos and the sheen of new paint — looses from its moorings and takes the night with it. It lists, then turns like a small,"
    "indifferent island. Lamps and the promise of pre-staged housing pitch into the black as if the sea had decided to reject the future someone bought for profit."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A hollow, metal groan as the container tips; when it goes, the sound is quieter than you expect — a soft, final shudder]
    hide noah_reyes
    hide marta_chen

    scene bg ch12_735866_6 at full_bg
    "You watch it go. There is a tight place behind your sternum where something yields and does not put itself back together. This is the tonic you and a thousand others tasted: loss made visible. The"
    "town has paid with property, not with people — and that bargain is not small solace. You feel the salt on your eyelashes like witness."
    "Noah's hands find you again, this time a grip in the small of your back when you falter. His breath is hot and quick. His words are small, hurried, real."
    show noah_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_reyes "We saved the market. We saved the east houses. We—' (he swallows) '—we lost the investor stockpile."
    "You let the thought move through you. There is anger, a cold thing shaped like injury. There is also the fierce, small warmth of the people who are breathing because of the work your hands and so many others did. That warmth costs and it is honest."

    menu:
        "Tell Noah what you really think about the investors as you both haul a wet rope":
            "Your words come out clipped and raw: 'They thought they could buy the tide.' Noah laughs, a short, sharp sound, and answers, 'They forgot how stubborn we are.' The laughter cracks into a sob, then steadies."
        "Hold your chest shut and keep working, saving words for after the wind":
            "You bite the words back and let your fingers burn on the rope. Noah watches you for a second, his jaw working. He doesn't push. He ties off the line and nods, a whole sentence in a small gesture."

